# agent-readiness-kit — Cursor rules

TypeScript Node.js CLI (`ark`) that audits repositories for AI-agent readiness.
No external API calls, no telemetry, no auth. Fully deterministic, filesystem-only.

## Before starting

Read AGENTS.md and docs/ARCHITECTURE.md before any non-trivial change.

## Module boundaries

| Module | Responsibility |
|--------|----------------|
| src/audit/checks/* | Category auditors — deterministic, test-covered |
| src/audit/auditRepo.ts | Orchestration and final score |
| src/config/* | .arkrc loading and validation (Zod) |
| src/generate/* | Safe starter file generation |
| src/report/* | Terminal, JSON, Markdown formatters |
| src/fs/* | writeFileSafe, glob helpers, existence checks |
| tests/* | Vitest specs — one per check minimum |

## Audit check rules

- Return `CategoryResult` with `id`, `label`, `score`, `maxScore`, `findings`.
- Always cap: `score = Math.min(MAX_SCORE, score)`.
- No network calls, no randomness, no side effects in checks.
- Use `fileExists`, `dirExists`, `findFiles` from src/fs/ — never raw `fs` in checks.
- Finding status: `'pass'` | `'warn'` | `'fail'` only.

## Safe-write

Use `writeFileSafe` for all generated output. Never `fs.writeFile` directly.
`writeFileSafe` skips existing files unless `--force` is passed — preserve this.

## Testing

- `pnpm test` must pass before finishing any task.
- Every check needs: full-score case, zero-score case, at least one edge case.
- Isolate tests in `os.tmpdir()` subdirectories; clean up in `afterEach`.

## Commit style

Lowercase conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `improve:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`.
No emoji. Summary ≤ 72 chars. Body explains why, not what.

## Scoring reference

| Category | Max |
|----------|-----|
| agent-instructions | 20 |
| architecture | 15 |
| workflow | 15 |
| testing | 15 |
| safety | 15 |
| navigability | 10 |
| prompt-assets | 10 |

## Forbidden without approval

- Breaking CLI command names or public flags
- Adding telemetry, network calls, or external API integrations
- Changing npm publish config or package name
- Disabling tests or skipping CI
